{"title_page": "Chery A11", "text_new": "{{Infobox automobile\n| name         = Chery A11\n| image        = Chery Fengyun SQR7160.jpg\n| aka          = Chery Fengyun<br />Chery Fulwin<br />Chery Windcloud\n| manufacturer = [[Chery]]\n| production   = 1999\u20132006 (China)<br />2008\u2013present (Jordan)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chery-jordan.com/cherya11.htm |title=Chery Autombile{{sic|hide=y}} |publisher=Chery-jordan.com |accessdate=2011-01-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101204051615/http://www.chery-jordan.com/cherya11.htm |archivedate=2010-12-04 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Harman |first=Alan |url=http://wardsauto.com/ar/chery_plant_jordan/ |title=Chery to Build Assembly Plant in Jordan |publisher=Wardsauto.com |date=2007-12-27 |accessdate=2010-12-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110926235447/http://wardsauto.com/ar/chery_plant_jordan/ |archive-date=2011-09-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| class        = [[Subcompact car]]\n| body_style   = 4-door [[Sedan (car)|sedan]]\n| engine       = 1.6 L ''[[ACTECO|SQR480]]'' [[Inline-four engine|I4]] ([[Petrol engine|petrol]])\n| transmission = 5-speed [[Manual transmission|manual]]\n| length       = \n| width        = \n| height       = \n| weight       = \n| wheelbase    = \n| successor    = [[Chery A15]]\n| related      = [[SEAT Toledo]] Mk. I\n}}\n\nThe '''Chery A11''' ({{CJKV|s=\u98ce\u4e91|p=Fengyun}}), also known as '''Fulwin''', '''Fengyun''' or '''Windcloud''', is [[Chery]]'s first car. Created without government approval, the Windcloud has nonetheless been the first step of Chery's success story and helped transform the Chinese automotive market from one dependent on foreign joint ventures.<ref name=\"Hessler1\">{{citation | title = Country Driving | last = Hessler | first = Peter | publisher = HarperCollins | location = NY, NY | year = 2010 | isbn = 978-0-06-180409-0 | pages = [https://archive.org/details/countrydrivingjo00hess_0/page/64 64\u201366] | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/countrydrivingjo00hess_0/page/64 }}</ref>\n\n==Development==\nThe A11 is essentially a rebadged first generation [[SEAT Toledo]], a model which was built by [[SEAT]] \u2013 i.e. the [[Spain|Spanish]] subsidiary of the [[Volkswagen group]] \u2013 from 1991 to 1998 and was based on the [[Volkswagen Group A platform#A2|Volkswagen Group A2 platform]]. This is the same platform used by [[FAW-VW Automobile]] for their successful, license-built [[Volkswagen Jetta#FAW Jetta|FAW-VW Jetta]]. Windcloud production indeed depended on secret side deals with the same parts suppliers as did FAW-VW. A later financial settlement out of court meant that Volkswagen agreed to abstain from a planned lawsuit.<ref name=\"Hessler2\">Hessler, p. 65</ref> The purchase of the Toledo blueprints was also executed in secret, in spite of SEAT being a Volkswagen subsidiary: all of these deft negotiations were the work of engineer Yin Tongyao, who had originally worked for Volkswagen's Chinese joint venture.<ref name=\"Hessler2\"/>\n[[File:Chery SQR7160 Windcloud.jpg|thumb|left|Chery Windcloud]]\nTongyao was originally poached by the government of [[Wuhu]], in [[Anhui province]], after they had reached the decision to develop a car for local production. Tongyao had also quietly purchased the production line for a rather outdated [[Ford]] engine (Ford 1.6 CVH) in England, which he then transferred to Anhui: the first engines left the production line in May 1999.<ref name=\"Hessler2\"/> This was to be the first engine installed in the Windcloud. It was later replaced by the more modern [[Tritec engine|Tritec]] and [[Chery ACTECO engine|Acteco]] engines. At the time, China had very strict regulations hindering the entry of new players into the automotive industry, so for nearly two years Chery was officially only producing \"automotive components\", albeit in a fully assembled form. In 2001, Chery finally received government permission to market their cars nationwide.<ref name=\"Hessler2\"/>\n\nThe Chery A11's production began in December 1999 as the ''CAC6340''. The name was changed to Fengyun, codenamed ''SQR7160'', in 2000,<ref name=WOC>{{cite book | title = World of Cars 2006\u00b72007 | publisher = Media Connection Sp. z o.o. | location = Warsaw, Poland | page = 237 | year = 2006 }}</ref> and Chinese production ended in 2006. The [[Chery A15]], first presented in 2003, is a facelifted Windcloud.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Chery Fulwin}}\n{{commons category|Chery Windcloud}}\n\n{{Chery Automobile}}\n\n[[Category:Chery vehicles|A11]]\n[[Category:Sedans]]\n[[Category:Subcompact cars]]\n[[Category:First car made by manufacturer]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox automobile\n| name         = Chery A11\n| image        = Chery Fengyun SQR7160.jpg\n| aka          = Chery Fengyun<br />Chery Fulwin<br />Chery Windcloud\n| manufacturer = [[Chery]]\n| production   = 1999\u20132006 (China)<br />2008\u2013present (Jordan)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chery-jordan.com/cherya11.htm |title=Chery Autombile |publisher=Chery-jordan.com |accessdate=2011-01-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101204051615/http://www.chery-jordan.com/cherya11.htm |archivedate=2010-12-04 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Harman |first=Alan |url=http://wardsauto.com/ar/chery_plant_jordan/ |title=Chery to Build Assembly Plant in Jordan |publisher=Wardsauto.com |date=2007-12-27 |accessdate=2010-12-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110926235447/http://wardsauto.com/ar/chery_plant_jordan/ |archive-date=2011-09-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| class        = [[Subcompact car]]\n| body_style   = 4-door [[Sedan (car)|sedan]]\n| engine       = 1.6 L ''[[ACTECO|SQR480]]'' [[Inline-four engine|I4]] ([[Petrol engine|petrol]])\n| transmission = 5-speed [[Manual transmission|manual]]\n| length       = \n| width        = \n| height       = \n| weight       = \n| wheelbase    = \n| successor    = [[Chery A15]]\n| related      = [[SEAT Toledo]] Mk. I\n}}\n\nThe '''Chery A11''' ({{CJKV|s=\u98ce\u4e91|p=Fengyun}}), also known as '''Fulwin''', '''Fengyun''' or '''Windcloud''', is [[Chery]]'s first car. Created without government approval, the Windcloud has nonetheless been the first step of Chery's success story and helped transform the Chinese automotive market from one dependent on foreign joint ventures.<ref name=\"Hessler1\">{{citation | title = Country Driving | last = Hessler | first = Peter | publisher = HarperCollins | location = NY, NY | year = 2010 | isbn = 978-0-06-180409-0 | pages = [https://archive.org/details/countrydrivingjo00hess_0/page/64 64\u201366] | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/countrydrivingjo00hess_0/page/64 }}</ref>\n\n==Development==\nThe A11 is essentially a rebadged first generation [[SEAT Toledo]], a model which was built by [[SEAT]] \u2013 i.e. the [[Spain|Spanish]] subsidiary of the [[Volkswagen group]] \u2013 from 1991 to 1998 and was based on the [[Volkswagen Group A platform#A2|Volkswagen Group A2 platform]]. This is the same platform used by [[FAW-VW Automobile]] for their successful, license-built [[Volkswagen Jetta#FAW Jetta|FAW-VW Jetta]]. Windcloud production indeed depended on secret side deals with the same parts suppliers as did FAW-VW. A later financial settlement out of court meant that Volkswagen agreed to abstain from a planned lawsuit.<ref name=\"Hessler2\">Hessler, p. 65</ref> The purchase of the Toledo blueprints was also executed in secret, in spite of SEAT being a Volkswagen subsidiary: all of these deft negotiations were the work of engineer Yin Tongyao, who had originally worked for Volkswagen's Chinese joint venture.<ref name=\"Hessler2\"/>\n[[File:Chery SQR7160 Windcloud.jpg|thumb|left|Chery Windcloud]]\nTongyao was originally poached by the government of [[Wuhu]], in [[Anhui province]], after they had reached the decision to develop a car for local production. Tongyao had also quietly purchased the production line for a rather outdated [[Ford]] engine (Ford 1.6 CVH) in England, which he then transferred to Anhui: the first engines left the production line in May 1999.<ref name=\"Hessler2\"/> This was to be the first engine installed in the Windcloud. It was later replaced by the more modern [[Tritec engine|Tritec]] and [[Chery ACTECO engine|Acteco]] engines. At the time, China had very strict regulations hindering the entry of new players into the automotive industry, so for nearly two years Chery was officially only producing \"automotive components\", albeit in a fully assembled form. In 2001, Chery finally received government permission to market their cars nationwide.<ref name=\"Hessler2\"/>\n\nThe Chery A11's production began in December 1999 as the ''CAC6340''. The name was changed to Fengyun, codenamed ''SQR7160'', in 2000,<ref name=WOC>{{cite book | title = World of Cars 2006\u00b72007 | publisher = Media Connection Sp. z o.o. | location = Warsaw, Poland | page = 237 | year = 2006 }}</ref> and Chinese production ended in 2006. The [[Chery A15]], first presented in 2003, is a facelifted Windcloud.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Chery Fulwin}}\n{{commons category|Chery Windcloud}}\n\n{{Chery Automobile}}\n\n[[Category:Chery vehicles|A11]]\n[[Category:Sedans]]\n[[Category:Subcompact cars]]\n[[Category:First car made by manufacturer]]\n", "name_user": "Will Sandberg", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chery_A11"}
{"title_page": "Tom Norris (record producer)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Tom Norris\n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| image            = \n| birth_name       = Thomas Norris\n| alias            = {{hlist|getyoursnackon}}\n| birth_place      = [[Falmouth, Massachusetts]], United States\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1991|7|11}}\n| origin           = Los Angeles, California, United States\n| genre            = {{hlist|Dance|Pop|[[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]}}\n| occupation       = {{hlist|Record producer|[[recording engineer]]|[[mixing engineer]]|[[mastering engineer]]|songwriter}}\n| instrument       = {{hlist|[[Ableton Live]]|[[FL Studio]]|Guitar|keyboards|piano}}\n| years_active     = 2010\u2013present\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[Skrillex]]|[[Zedd]]|[[Grey (duo)]]}}\n| website          = {{URL|getyoursnackon.com/}}\n}}\n'''Tom Norris''' is an American [[mixing engineer]], [[sound design]]er, record producer, [[mastering engineer]], and songwriter from Los Angeles, California. Norris is best known for his mixing and production work for several prominent artists in the music industry, including [[Skrillex]], [[Zedd]], [[Grey (duo)|Grey]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dailybruin.com/2017/05/09/on-the-rise-grey/|title=On the Rise: Grey|date=May 9, 2017|website=Daily Bruin}}</ref>, [[The Weeknd]], [[Camila Cabello]], [[XXXTENTACION]], and [[Mariah Carey]], among others.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youredm.com/2019/02/06/meet-tom-norris-one-of-the-biggest-names-in-edm-youve-never-heard-of/|title=Meet Tom Norris, One of the Biggest Names in EDM You've Never Heard Of|last=Meadow|first=Matthew|date=February 6, 2019|website=Your EDM|access-date=12 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n\n=== Grammy Awards ===\n{{awards table}}\n!{{Abbr|Ref.|References}}\n|-\n|[[61st Annual Grammy Awards|2019]]\n| ''[[The Middle (Zedd, Maren Morris and Grey song)|The Middle]]'' <small>(as mixer)</small>\n| [[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]]\n|{{nominated}}\n|rowspan=\"19\"|<ref>https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/tom-norris</ref>\n|-\n|[[62nd Annual Grammy Awards|2020]]\n| ''[[Midnight Hour (Skrillex, Boys Noize and Ty Dolla Sign song)|Midnight Hour]]'' <small>(as mixer)</small>\n| Best Dance Recording\n|{{nominated}}\n{{end}}\n\n=== iHeartRadio Music Awards ===\n{{awards table}}\n!{{Abbr|Ref.|References}}\n|-\n|2019\n| ''[[The Middle (Zedd, Maren Morris and Grey song)|The Middle]]'' <small>(as mixer)</small>\n| Song of the Year\n|{{won}}\n|rowspan=\"19\"|<ref>https://news.iheart.com/featured/iheartradio-music-awards/content/2019-03-14-2019-iheartradio-music-awards-winners-see-the-complete-list/</ref>\n{{end}}\n\n=== Billboard Music Awards ===\n{{awards table}}\n!{{Abbr|Ref.|References}}\n|-\n|2019\n| ''[[The Middle (Zedd, Maren Morris and Grey song)|The Middle]]'' <small>(as mixer)</small>\n| Top Dance/Electronic Song\n|{{won}}\n|rowspan=\"19\"|<ref>https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/awards/8509655/billboard-music-awards-2019-winners-list/</ref>\n{{end}}\n\n== Discography<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/artist/5200739-Tom-Norris-2|title=Discogs Discography|date=February 5, 2019|publisher=discogs}}</ref>==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Artists\n!Album\n!Credit\n|-\n| rowspan=\"46\" |2019\n|4\u00c6M\n|[[Grimes (musician)|Grimes]]\n|Non-album single\n|Mixer\n|-\n|THAT BITCH\n|[[Bea Miller]]\n|Non-album single\n|Mixer\n|-\n|Good On You\n|[[Krewella]], [[Nucleya]]\n|Non-album single\n|Mixer\n|-\n|Greenlights\n|[[Krewella]]\n|Non-album single\n|Mixer\n|-\n|Body Back\n|[[Gryffin]], Maia Wright\n|Gravity\n|Mixer\n|-\n|Hero\n|[[Said the Sky]], Dabin, Olivver the Kid\n|Non-album single\n|Mixer\n|-\n|Ghost\n|[[Krewella]]\n|Non-album single\n|Mixer\n|-\n|Daydreams\n|[[Arty (musician)|Arty]], Cimo Frankel\n|Non-album single\n|Co-producer, mixer\n|-\n|habits\n|ilo ilo\n|Non-album single\n|Mixe