044c. \u0422\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u0434\u0440\u0435\u0432\u043d\u0435\u0440\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0438 \u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0438\u0441\u043a\u0443\u0441\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u0432 \u0440\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u0438\u0441\u043a\u0443\u0441\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435 XVIII \u2014 \u043d\u0430\u0447\u0430\u043b\u0430 XX \u0432\u0435\u043a\u0430\n|place=\u041c.\n|publisher=\u0413\u0430\u043b\u0430\u0440\u0442\n|year=1997\n|pages=431\n|isbn=5-269-00930-7\n|ref=\u041a\u0438\u0440\u0438\u0447\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e}}\n*{{cite book\n|author=\u041a\u043b\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0432, \u041f. \u042e.\n|title=\u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0438\u043b \u0412\u0440\u0443\u0431\u0435\u043b\u044c\n|place=Moscow\n|publisher=\u0410\u0440\u0442-\u0420\u043e\u0434\u043d\u0438\u043a\n|year=2001\n|pages=72\n|isbn=5-88896-053-5\n|ref=\u041a\u043b\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0432}}\n*{{cite book\n|author=\u041a\u043b\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0432, \u041f. \u042e. \n|title=\u041c\u043e\u0434\u0435\u0440\u043d \u0432 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438\n|place=Moscow\n|publisher=\u0410\u0440\u0442-\u0420\u043e\u0434\u043d\u0438\u043a\n|year=2010\n|pages=416\n|isbn=978-5-40400025-2\n|ref=\u041a\u043b\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0432}}\n*{{cite book\n|author=\u041a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043d, \u041a. \u0410.\n|title=\u041a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0442\u0438\u043d \u041a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043d \u0432\u0441\u043f\u043e\u043c\u0438\u043d\u0430\u0435\u0442\u2026\n|place=Moscow\n|publisher=\u0418\u0437\u043e\u0431\u0440. \u0438\u0441\u043a-\u0432\u043e\n|year=1990\n|pages=608\n|isbn=5-85200-118-X\n|ref=\u041a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043d}}\n*{{cite book\n|author=\u041a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043b\u0451\u0432\u0430, \u0421.\n|title=\u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0438\u043b \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0412\u0440\u0443\u0431\u0435\u043b\u044c\n|place=Moscow\n|publisher=\u041a\u043e\u043c\u0441. \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0434\u0430\n|year=2010\n|pages=48\n|ref=\u041a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043b\u0451\u0432\u0430}}\n*{{cite book\n|author=\u041d\u0430\u0449\u043e\u043a\u0438\u043d\u0430, \u041c. \u0412.\n|title=\u0410\u0440\u0445\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440\u044b \u043c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043c\u043e\u0434\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0430. \u0422\u0432\u043e\u0440\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0440\u0435\u0442\u044b\n|place=Moscow\n|publisher=\u0416\u0438\u0440\u0430\u0444\n|year=2005\n|pages=304\n|isbn=5-89832-043-1\n|ref=\u041d\u0430\u0449\u043e\u043a\u0438\u043d\u0430}}\n*{{cite book\n|author=\u041b.\u041c.\u0421\u0430\u0432\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430\n|title=\u0420\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0441\u043b\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0430\u044f \u043a\u043d\u0438\u0433\u0430 \u0434\u0432\u043e\u0440\u044f\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0433\u0443\u0431\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0438\u0438\n|place=Moscow\n|year=1914\n|pages=\n|ref=\u0421\u0430\u0432\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430}}\n*{{cite book\n|author=\u0421\u0443\u0437\u0434\u0430\u043b\u0435\u0432, \u041f. \u041a.\n|title=\u0412\u0440\u0443\u0431\u0435\u043b\u044c. \u041c\u0443\u0437\u044b\u043a\u0430. \u0422\u0435\u0430\u0442\u0440\n|place=Moscow\n|publisher=\u0418\u0437\u043e\u0431\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u0438\u0441\u043a\u0443\u0441\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e\n|year=1983\n|pages=367\n|ref=\u0421\u0443\u0437\u0434\u0430\u043b\u0435\u0432}}\n*{{cite book\n|author=\u0421\u0443\u0437\u0434\u0430\u043b\u0435\u0432, \u041f. \u041a.\n|title=\u0412\u0440\u0443\u0431\u0435\u043b\u044c. \u041b\u0438\u0447\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c. \u041c\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0437\u0437\u0440\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435. \u041c\u0435\u0442\u043e\u0434\n|publisher=\u0418\u0437\u043e\u0431\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u0438\u0441\u043a\u0443\u0441\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e\n|year=1984\n|pages=479\n|ref=\u0421\u0443\u0437\u0434\u0430\u043b\u0435\u0432}}\n*{{cite book\n|author=\u0422\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0431\u0443\u043a\u0438\u043d, \u041d. \u041c.\n|title=\u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0438\u043b \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0412\u0440\u0443\u0431\u0435\u043b\u044c\n|place=Moscow\n|publisher=\u0418\u0441\u043a\u0443\u0441\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e\n|year=1974\n|ref=\u0422\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0431\u0443\u043a\u0438\u043d}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category|Mikhail Vrubel|Michail Alexandrowitsch Wrubel}}\n* [http://www.tanais.info/art/en/vrubelab.html  Vrubel's Demon]  publication\n* [http://www.tanais.info/art/en/vrubel5more.html  Vrubel's Demon]   descriptions\n* [http://www.tanais.info/art/en/vrubel2ab.html  Vrubel and Ceramics]\n* [http://www.tanais.info/art/en/vrubel3ab.html   Vrubel and Decorative Panels]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100309033047/http://www.museum-online.ru/en/Postimpressionism/Mikhail_Alexandrovich_Vrubel Canvases and biography by Mikhail Alexandrovich Vrubel]\n* [http://www.russianartgallery.org/vrubel/ Works by Vrubel at the Russian Art Gallery]\n* [https://archive.is/19990821090307/http://www.rollins.edu/Foreign_Lang/Russian/vrubel.html Vrubel's short biography]\n* [http://vrubel.narod.ru Online Vrubel museum]\n* [http://www.abcgallery.com/V/vrubel/vrubel.html Mikhail Vrubel Gallery]\n* [http://www.phys.lsu.edu/students/alexey/ Mikhail Vrubel]\n; On Google Art Project\n* [http://www.googleartproject.com/museums/tretyakov/demon-sitting-191 Demon (sitting)]\n* [http://www.googleartproject.com/museums/tretyakov/princess-reverie-193 Princess Reverie]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vrubel, Mikhail}}\n[[Category:19th-century Russian painters]]\n[[Category:Russian male painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century Russian painters]]\n[[Category:Symbolist painters]]\n[[Category:Russian symbolism]]\n[[Category:Imperial Academy of Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:Art Nouveau painters]]\n[[Category:Post-impressionist painters]] \n[[Category:Russian watercolorists]] \n[[Category:Russian ceramists]]\n[[Category:1856 births]]\n[[Category:1910 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Omsk]]\n[[Category:Russian people of Danish descent]]\n[[Category:Russian people of Polish descent]]\n[[Category:Deaths from syphilis]]\n[[Category:Members of the Imperial Academy of Arts]]\n", "name_user": "Drjayjr", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eKiev and Odessa", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mikhail_Vrubel"}
{"title_page": "Kerch Strait ferry line", "text_new": "{|align=right style=\"border:#cccccc 1px solid;background-color:#fefefe; width:260px; margin-left:1em; \"\n|\n{{superimpose2\n|collapse=1\n|base=Kerch Strait Landsat.jpg\n|base_width=250px\n|base_caption=Satellite image of the Kerch Strait. Left side is [[Kerch Peninsula]], [[Crimea]]. Right side is [[Chushka Spit]], [[Taman Peninsula]], [[Russia]].\n|base_alt=\n|float=Green Dot.svg\n|float_width=10px\n|float_caption=Kerch\n|float_alt=Green dot that represents Kerch\n|link=Kerch\n|x=127|y=75\n|t3=<span style=\"background:white\">[[Kerch]]</span>\n|x3=90|y3=67\n|float2=Red Dot.svg\n|float2_width=10px\n|float2_caption=Chushka Spit\n|float2_alt=Red dot that represents Chushka Spit\n|link2=Chushka Spit\n|x2=143|y2=80\n|t2=<span style=\"background:white\">[[Chushka Spit]]</span>\n}}\n<small>Satellite image of Kerch Strait. Left side is [[Crimea]] (green dot represents [[Kerch]]). Right side is [[Taman Peninsula]], [[Russia]] (red dot represents [[Chushka Spit]].)</small>\n|}\n[[File:Kerch Strait Ferry, satellite image, 2018-03-05.jpg|thumb|300px|Kerch Strait ferry, satellite image [[Sentinel-2]], [[Port Krym]] (harbour Crimea) at top left corner,  [[Port Kavkaz]] (harbour Caucasus) at bottom right corner; two ferries are moving across the [[Strait of Kerch]].]]\nThe '''Kerch Strait ferry line''' ({{lang-ru|\u041a\u0435\u0440\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043f\u0430\u0440\u043e\u043c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0430 (also, \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0430 \u00ab\u041a\u0440\u044b\u043c \u2014 \u041a\u0430\u0432\u043a\u0430\u0437\u00bb)}}, {{lang-uk|\u041a\u0435\u0440\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043c\u043d\u0430 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0430}}) is the [[Russia|Russian]]\u2013operated [[ferry]] connection across the [[Strait of Kerch]] that connects the [[Crimean Peninsula]] and [[Krasnodar Krai]].\n\nThe ferry runs across the narrowest part of the strait (about 5 km) between [[Port Krym]] (harbour Crimea) by the city of [[Kerch]] and [[Port Kavkaz]] (harbour Caucasus) on the [[Chushka Spit]], on the site of former [[Kerch railway bridge]]. It carries passengers, automotive and railroad transport. The ferry is on the [[European route E97]] and connects its parts, [[A290 highway (Russia)|\u0410290 (formerly M25)]] and [[Highway M17 (Ukraine)|\u041c-17]] highways.\n\n==History==\nThe ferry line was established in 1953. From 1993 to 2004 railroad transportation was suspended due to replacement of aged train-ferries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parovoz.com/spravka/ferries.html|title=\u0416\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0437\u043d\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0436\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043f\u0430\u0440\u043e\u043c\u044b \u0432 \u0431\u044b\u0432\u0448\u0435\u043c \u0421\u0421\u0421\u0420 (Rail ferries in the former USSR)|accessdate=March 22, 2014|language=ru}}</ref>\n\nSince the [[dissolution of the Soviet Union]], it was administered by [[Russia]] and [[Ukraine]] through the joint venture \u201cCrimea-Kuban Crossing\u201d. In 1998, this company was reorganized into a Ukrainian state-owned enterprise \"Kerch Strait ferry line\". On 17 March 2014, during the [[annexation of Crimea by the Russian Federation]], the company was nationalised by the [[Republic of Crimea]].\n\nThe use of the ferry rose sharply after the annexation, and in June 2015, the ferry operator considered a daily passenger count of 11,000 normal.<ref>http://www.c-inform.info/news/id/24379</ref>\n\nThe 2018 opening of the road section of the new [[Crimean Bridge]], crossing the strait about 10 km further south, and the projected 2019-2020 opening of the railway section of that bridge, have greatly reduced demand for the ferry.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nImage:Kerch Ferry Yeysk.jpg|Yeysk car-ferry\nImage:Kerch AnnenkovKrym.jpg|Annenkov train-ferry\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Crimean Bridge]]\n* [[Kerch\u2013Yenikale Canal]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Crimea-stub}}\n{{Russia-transport-stub}}\n\n{{coord|45.3532|36.6504|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Ferries of Ukraine]]\n[[Category:Ferry transport in Russia]]\n[[Category:Transport in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:Transport in Crimea]]\n[[Category:Kerch Strait]]\n[[Category:Krasnodar Krai]]\n[[Category:1953 establishments in the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Transport in the Soviet Union]]\n", "text_old": "{|align=right style=\"border:#cccccc 1px solid;background-color:#fefefe; width:260px; margin-left:1em; \"\n|\n{{superimpose2\n|collapse=1\n|base=Kerch Strait Landsat.jpg\n|base_width=250px\n|base_caption=Satellite image of the Kerch Strait. Left side is [[Kerch Peninsula]], [[Crimea]]. Right side is [[Chushka Spit]], [[Taman Peninsula]], [[Russia]].\n|base_alt=\n|float=Green Dot.svg\n|float_width=10px\n|float_caption=Kerch\n|float_alt=Green dot that represents Kerch\n|link=Kerch\n|x=127|y=75\n|t3=<span style=\"background:white\">[[Kerch]]</span>\n|x3=90|y3=67\n|float2=Red Dot.svg\n|float2_width=10px\n|float2_caption=Chushka Spit\n|float2_alt=Red dot that represents Chushka Spit\n|link2=Chushka Spit\n|x2=143|y2=80\n|t2=<span style=\"background:white\">[[Chushka Spit]]</span>\n}}\n<small>Satellite image of Kerch Strait. Left side is [[Crimea]] (green dot represents [[Kerch]]). Right side is [[Taman Peninsula]], [[Russia]] (red dot represents [[Chushka Spit]].)</small>\n|}\n[[File:Kerch Strait Ferry, satellite image, 2018-03-05.jpg|thumb|300px|Kerch Strait ferry, satellite image [[Sentinel-2]], [[Port Krym]] (harbour Crimea) at top left corner,  [[Port Kavkaz]] (harbour Caucasus) at bottom right corner; two ferries are moving across the [[Strait of Kerch]].]]\nThe '''Kerch Strait ferry line''' ({{lang-ru|\u041a\u0435\u0440\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043f\u0430\u0440\u043e\u043c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0430 (also, \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0430 \u00ab\u041a\u0440\u044b\u043c \u2014 \u041a\u0430\u0432\u043a\u0430\u0437\u00bb)}}, {{lang-uk|\u041a\u0435\u0440\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043c\u043d\u0430 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0430}}) is the [[Russia|Russian]]\u2013operated [[ferry]] connection across the [[Strait of Kerch]] that connects the [[Crimean Peninsula]] and [[Krasnodar Krai]].\n\nThe ferry runs across the narrowest part of the strait (about 5 km) between [[Port Krym]] (harbour Crimea) by the city of [[Kerch]] and [[Port Kavkaz]] (harbour Caucasus) on the [[Chushka Spit]], on the site of former [[Kerch railway bridge]]. It carries passengers, automotive and railroad transport. The ferry is on the [[European route E97]] and connects its parts, [[A290 highway (Russia)|\u0410290 (formerly M25)]] and [[Highway M17 (Ukraine)|\u041c-17]] highways.\n\n==History==\nThe ferry line was established in 1953. From 1993 to 2004 railroad transportation was suspended due to replacement of aged train-ferries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parovoz.com/spravka/ferries.html|title=\u0416\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0437\u043d\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0436\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043f\u0430\u0440\u043e\u043c\u044b \u0432 \u0431\u044b\u0432\u0448\u0435\u043c \u0421\u0421\u0421\u0420 (Rail ferries in the former USSR)|accessdate=March 22, 2014|language=ru}}</ref>\n\nSince the [[dissolution of the Soviet Union]], it was administered by [[Russia]] and [[Ukraine]] through the joint venture \u201cCrimea-Kuban Crossing\u201d. In 1998, this company was reorganized into an Ukrainian state-owned enterprise \"Kerch Strait ferry line\". On 17 March 2014, during the [[annexation of Crimea by the Russian Federation]], the company was nationalised by the [[Republic of Crimea]].\n\nThe use of the ferry rose sharply after the annexation, and in June 2015, the ferry operator considered a daily passenger count of 11,000 normal.<ref>http://www.c-inform.info/news/id/24379</ref>\n\nThe 2018 opening of the road section of the new [[Crimean Bridge]], crossing the strait about 10 km further south, and the projected 2019-2020 opening of the railway section of that bridge, have greatly reduced demand for the ferry.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nImage:Kerch Ferry Yeysk.jpg|Yeysk car-ferry\nImage:Kerch AnnenkovKrym.jpg|Annenkov train-ferry\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Crimean Bridge]]\n* [[Kerch\u2013Yenikale Canal]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Crimea-stub}}\n{{Russia-transport-stub}}\n\n{{coord|45.3532|36.6504|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Ferries of Ukraine]]\n[[Category:Ferry transport in Russia]]\n[[Category:Transport in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:Transport in Crimea]]\n[[Category:Kerch Strait]]\n[[Category:Krasnodar Krai]]\n[[Category:1953 establishments in the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Transport in the Soviet Union]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: an Ukrainian \u2192 a Ukrainian", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kerch_Strait_ferry_line"}
